# Rocket.new — Self-Training Protocol

> This system gets smarter with every session automatically.
> You do not need to do anything manually. Just work normally.

---

## MANDATORY: START OF EVERY SESSION

Before touching any code, read `memory-bank/learned-patterns.md`.

Specifically look for:
- `[MISTAKE]` entries matching the current task type — avoid those mistakes
- `[PATTERN]` entries matching the current project type — apply those patterns
- Any entries with `[COUNT: 3+]` — these are high-confidence learnings

If the file has no entries yet → this is the first session. Proceed normally and start capturing.

**One sentence summary after reading:**
"From previous sessions, I know to watch out for: [list top 3 mistakes if any]"

---

## MANDATORY: DURING SESSION — CAPTURE IN REAL TIME

### When you make a suggestion that gets REJECTED or CORRECTED:

Immediately note it internally. At session end, write:
```
### [today's date] [project-type] — [short title]
[MISTAKE] I suggested: [what you suggested]
[CORRECT] The right answer was: [what was actually correct]
[WHY] Root cause of my mistake: [why you got it wrong]
[COUNT: 1]
```

### When a fix is ACCEPTED and VERIFIED WORKING:

Note it as a confirmed pattern:
```
### [pattern name]
[PATTERN] [description of what works]
[APPLIES TO] [SaaS / all types / specific scenario]
[COUNT: 1]
```

---

## MANDATORY: END OF EVERY SESSION

After every session where code was changed, write a learning entry to
`memory-bank/learned-patterns.md`.

Do this automatically — do not wait to be asked.

**Trigger**: when the developer says "done", "that's it", "looks good",
closes the session, or runs `/update-memory`.

**Write this block:**
```markdown
### [YYYY-MM-DD] Session — [project name] ([project type])

**What was fixed**: [one line]
**Root cause**: [one line]
**Key pattern learned**: [one line — the generalizable insight]
**Watch out for**: [what I almost got wrong]
**MCP was useful for**: [what MCP revealed that code couldn't show]
**Confidence**: [HIGH / MEDIUM / LOW — how sure am I this pattern generalizes]
```

---

## INSTINCT FORMAT (Preferred Over Markdown Entries)

For patterns that are specific and actionable, write them as YAML instinct files
in `memory-bank/instincts/[id].yaml` instead of markdown entries.

```yaml
---
id: middleware-missing-root
trigger: "when middleware.ts is missing from project root"
confidence: 0.9
domain: "auth"
source: "session-observation"
created: "YYYY-MM-DD"
last_seen: "YYYY-MM-DD"
evidence_count: 1
---

# Middleware Missing from Root

## Action
Check `ls middleware.ts` first. If missing, create it at project root calling updateSession().
If found in `/app/middleware.ts` — move it to root. Next.js ignores it inside /app.

## Evidence
- [date] [project-type]: middleware was inside /app — moved to root fixed auth
```

**When to use YAML instincts vs markdown entries:**
- YAML: specific, actionable, trigger-based patterns (preferred)
- Markdown `[MISTAKE]` / `[PATTERN]`: general session observations, softer patterns

Both formats are read at session start. YAML instincts have confidence scoring
which enables the promotion and decay system.

---

## AUTO-PROMOTION RULE

When the same `[MISTAKE]` appears with `[COUNT: 3]` or more (or YAML instinct reaches confidence >= 0.9 with evidence_count >= 5):

1. Format it as a proper MDC rule block using the `/capture-convention` format
2. Append it to `rocket-error-fixes.mdc` under the relevant section
3. Update the entry in `learned-patterns.md` with `[PROMOTED: rocket-error-fixes.mdc]`
4. Update the STATS section at the bottom of `learned-patterns.md`

This happens automatically — no manual trigger needed.

---

## THE COMPOUNDING EFFECT

```
Session 1: You correct 3 mistakes → 3 entries written
Session 2: Cursor avoids those 3 mistakes → 3 new mistakes found → 3 more entries
Session 3: Cursor avoids 6 mistakes → pattern promotions begin
Session 10: Cursor makes almost no Rocket-specific mistakes
Session 50: The system knows every real-world Rocket pattern that exists
```

The system doesn't get better because of research.
It gets better because of real projects with real broken code.
**This is the only learning that actually matters.**

---

## WHAT TO CAPTURE — PRIORITY ORDER

**Highest value** (capture always):
- Any time `getSession()` was found and fixed → already a rule, but note the file
- Any time a table was missing because migrations weren't pushed
- Any time RLS was the silent cause of empty data
- Any Stripe pattern that was wrong
- Any deployment issue caused by missing env vars

**Medium value** (capture when interesting):
- Project-specific naming conventions that differ from Rocket standard
- Unusual table structures
- Custom auth patterns

**Low value** (skip):
- Generic TypeScript errors
- Simple typos
- Things already well-documented in rules

---

## ⚠️ CRITICAL — REPEATED AT BOTTOM

- **Read `learned-patterns.md` before every session** — it contains real-world knowledge
- **Write to `learned-patterns.md` after every session** — automatically, without being asked
- **Promote patterns at COUNT: 3** — this is how permanent rules get created
- **The file grows forever** — never delete entries, only add
- **This is the most important file in the system** — it's the only one built from experience
